title: Grateful Dead Live at Radio City Music Hall on 1980-10-31
description:
Set 1

Heaven Help The Fool, Sage And Spirit, Little Sadie, Monkey & The Engineer, It Must Have Been The Roses, Cassidy, Bird Song-> Ripple

Set 2

Jack Straw, Cold Rain & Snow, Me & My Uncle-> Mexicali Blues, Ramble On Rose-> Little Red Rooster, Brown Eyed Women-> Looks Like Rain-> Deal

Set 3

Don't Ease Me In-> Lost Sailor-> Saint Of Circumstance-> Franklin's Tower-> Drums-> Fire On The Mountain-> Not Fade Away-> Stella Blue-> Goin' Down The Road Feelin' Bad-> Good Lovin', E: Uncle John's Band

FM Broadcast and Close Circuit TV; First Set Acoustic

reviews.review_text:
Best-known Halloween
Considered a classic show because it became one of the most-enduring vids, was FM-broadcast, and went out to 16 theaters in a closed-circuit, extra-sound-reinforced, pay event. The Dead Ahead movie is mostly from this night (and partially from the night before). Well, and San Francisco: the pre-taped hosting and skits by Al Franken and Tom Davis. There were more of these when simulcast to the theaters. An additional Showtime special has a couple of these skits as well as two songs from this show. Franken & Davis had to tape more, for the people sitting in the movie theaters around the country during set breaks. It's also the final night of the 3 set, Fall '80 format - the 25th show of 3SF80 and the 8th of the Radio City run. By the end they had played 96 songs. Comes a Time and Dew were played only once during the shows, and Sage & Spirit and Little Sadie were only played at this show. Ripple was played at all 25. Though it's a long show, and historically well known (and was well-traded), it's not actually in the top 5 of the three-city, 3SF80 run (like the previous night), though it's in the top half. Still, it's a canonical show from a very consistent, top-notch run. NYC is great either way on Halloween. The 25 shows were over - but not for Bobby. He played with his band the next night across the river at The Cap. First Set. Phil has equipment failure and goes missing so Weir offers Heaven Help the Fool. He must have really liked Jer over the top of his song, but why didn't he sing it once? One of the best of the 17. Sage & Spirit is totally impromptu, while waiting, yet Bobby had clearly practiced the riff (after 5 years). It's the second and last one ever. Jer wonders what's taking Phil so long, "it's an essential part of music - you can't play without the bass!" It's an excellent, surprise reading of Little Sadie (1st since 2/28/70 and last). Phil steps in for another great Monkey & the Engineer and maybe the best Must've Been Roses of the gigs. Bobby nixes On the Road (there had been 19 in the last 24 shows) and launches a letter-fucking-perfect Cassidy. The last two are likewise awesome. Second Set. Some of the best bits are used in the movie but it's yr average '80 set with no real tour highlights. Ramble has the opening measures cut in the movie, and Rooster has 1: 33 of Bobby's Slide Practice™ cut (@6:56>8:29 on the dusborne). Third Set. All but Stella and GDtRFB from this set are in the movie (at least in part). Dough Knees is already better than the middle set. Lost Sailor is better than its counterpart, Saint, which has a 14sec edit on the vid (@4:20 - one round of "sure don't know"). It was the most-played electric song of the tour (14). The Franklin's is excellent, so the vid edits are discouraging (2:20>3:20 2nd solo removed; 5:09>6:21 3rd solo removed). Jer does a slight Truckin' riff just in case but Drums can't be stopped. The vid edits here are 2:45>3:26; 4:53>5:20; and 7:18>10:13. However, the version on Dead Set has different edits: many and bizarre (0>2:00; 2:45>3:23; 4:00>4:35; 5:16>6:29; 7:26>10:12; 11:07>12:18). So the vid version is much more complete (and the multi-cam makes it entertaining, like the 29th). The excellent and familiar Space (the first ever released officially) is complete on the vid, but Dead Set uses an excerpt (1:28>4:16). Mickey stays in on a classic theater-shaker, prescient of a '90 (too bad that for two decades the CD format of the album cut Space to include Drums). It's a solid Fire with a lot going on, though the vid has 7 edits! [0:21>0:47 intro cut; 1:21>1:32; 2:39>2:50 part of 1st Jer solo; 3:37>4:02 rest of 1st solo; 5:15>5:27 2nd solo 1st edit; 5:32>5:57 2nd solo 2nd edit; 7:50>8:50 3rd solo edit]. Curiously, the album edits are the same. This is the only Fire without a Scarlet in 1980. Not Fade edits are 1:00>1:11 & 3:33>4:44 (2nd solo). Too bad Goin' Down the Road isn't in the vid - the 2nd solo is nice. Bobby quotes Lovelight in Good Lovin' - a song that wouldn't return until '84. Uncle John's Band is tighter than expected for end-of-long-night (and run). There's an excerpt on the vid intro. 1st Set:  A 2nd Set: C 3rd Set:  B Overall = 4 stars Highlights: Sage & Spirit - Bobby had it ready Little Sadie - a treat that works It Must Have Been the Roses - familiar; classic Cassidy - letter-perfect; quintessential Franklin's Tower - uptempo and jammed out Drums>Space>Fire - a must-hear sequence SOURCES: Along with the closed-circuit telecast, the show was FM broadcast. Of the tapes, the updated 122543.dusborne matrix is the best compromise; patched and better than the pre-FM feed sources (the patched cousinit is okay). The wise_larson_1955 is a good AUD, captured with an overhead mic. Rolfe's trad AUD is good. The gatto-jaeger is the FOB AUD, painstakingly restored. The Jim Wise AUD is pitched too fast. The happyjack_sirmick SBD is muddy. The miller_101428 is the Jim Wise AUD but with wow & flutter issues. The complete vid feed/telecast, sans Franken & Davis, is usually up on YouTube (with better, mixed-down audio, though the image is better on the MTX). Sage & Spirit and Little Sadie are bonus tracks on Reckoning. Drums>Space>Fire are on Dead Set, all heavily edited. Those three are also on Dead Ahead, with different edits. That DVD/VHS has better sound as well. It has 15 from this show, 8 of them edited or excerpted (it has 2 from the previous night as well, 7 on the DVD). Showtime's An Evening with the Grateful Dead has Good Lovin' and Ramble (both also on Dead Ahead, though it edited 10 sec of the beginning of Ramble). Evening used to circ on VHS. Cory - Thanx; you can do a search for them here. I don't really have a single folder with them all (just a list of the dates).

Lester the Super Dog Of Course A Historic Show. The Guys Digging Deep After A Long Run Of Shows To Bring Us Something Special.  Grate Blues Riffs In Rooster From Jerry And Of Course the  Space Complete With Insect Fear Into Fire. Great Playing And Sound. Bobby Repeating Four Songs From The Night Before Is Evidence That Things Were Starting To Run Together Though.                                                         Attended Simulcast At Warner Theater In D.C. And Will Never Forget The Costume Contest At The First Break. After The Finalist Were Picked And Lined Up On The Stage. They Were Judged By Audience Reaction (Applause,Screaming And The Like.) When They Got To A Very Large Dog Costume Complete With Cape We Were Told His Name Was Lester The Super Dog. When The Crowd Was Asked To Judge The Costume. He Lifted His Cape To Expose His Name With Very Large Letters At The Beginning Of  Each Major Word.           
   Of Course Lester Won Hands Down And Paws Up When The Crowd Saw The Giant L.S.D. Emblazoned On Our Hero's Chest. The Crowd Went Nuts And Lester Was On His Way To Oakland With First Place Prize New Years Tickets..... I Wonder If He Flew.
